US to reduce fighter plane patrols in domestic airspace
( Washington road transmission ) us defense department officials said on Monday that the bush administration has decided to lower the alert level of air force fighter patrols that have been in place since the september 11 attacks , but will still maintain a relatively small number of patrols and keep aircraft on standby at the runway .
the department of defense said that day - and - night patrols have already cost the air force 500 million us dollars ( about 900 million Singapore dollars ) , but patrols over washington will continue . as for the new york area , air patrols will be stopped , except for occasional emergencies .
the airport and airlines have stepped up security measures following the september 11 incident before the authorities decided to reduce or stop air patrols .
Defense department spokesman Clark told reporters : we are studying a plan that combines different methods , including fighter patrols over certain regions , continuous fighter patrols based on ad hoc decisions , and standby measures for different levels of runways .
runway standby means that the aircraft is in a state of readiness for emergency take-off at any time .
she also said that the alert would be adjusted at any time according to the level of threat .
